cs.NE, cs.DS, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.SY

This paper presents a theoretical analysis of an evolution strategy applied to a constrained linear optimization problem. The focus is on the inner workings of the algorithm, and the analysis involves modeling the state of the strategy with random variables and introducing a stochastic iterative mapping. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the use of non-linear difference equations and the comparison with real algorithm runs suggest that the paper may also belong to the Dynamical Systems (cs.DS) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The application of the algorithm to a constrained problem and the use of cumulative step size adaptation suggest that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the use of a stochastic iterative mapping suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
